title: For Sale/Trade:  WWII ISSUE ENFIELD MADE BY PARKER HALE RARE
postcontent: This rifle is legitimate. Ive had this confirmed by several professionals who specialize in WWII arms. Built by Franz (for short) and contracted through Parker Hale Manufactured in March of 1943. Judging by the markings on the rifle there is a lot to say. The proofs indicate it was issued to British Army and not to new Zealand or some other place. Its a MKI No.4, a common model, HOWEVER the Parker Hale variants are somewhat rare. It does have the Original JC stock and butplate, numbers matching bolt and reciever chambered in .303 british (faster than 30-06) and even has the original sling. Has one detatchable magazine and 40rds. The rifle shoots great, and has ZERO issues, headspace was checked today by a gunsmith and its perfect. The bore does show wear, this was a war weapon, so its been broken in to say the least. None the less its a tack driver open sights from 200yds. Dont try to offer me $300 for this one. Its not one from the back of The Shotgun News. This one is a rare one. If you know enfields, come and have a look at the markings, come and shoot it. Its a cherry.

title: For Sale:  Romanian RPK AK47 AES-10B Paratrooper used in IRAQ by SOC-USA AK-47 AES-10B
postcontent:
Not only is this an EXTREMELY rare RPK variant, but this AES-10B was sent to Iraq and came back to the states. This gun was used in the SWA (Iraq/Afghanistan) Theater of Operation by US Military Contractor SOC-USA. These were recently bought back by CAI and resold to the public. They are now sold out. Very few of these were sold to the public. Don't miss your change to own a very rare gun that was actually used in a war zone. This is quite the special opportunity. 

These guns ranged from new condition to good condition. This one is in very good overall condition and has seen by my estimate no more than a couple hundred rounds. It has been test fired. Some, but not all of the rifles, came back with a rack number painted on the wood forgrip - this is one of them. 


This is the description from Century Arms regarding the paratrooper RPK rifles.
These rifles are semi-automatic only version of the Romanian RPK‚Äôs issued to elite paratrooper forces during the Communist Ceausescu Regime. This extremely rare variant is built using the small cache of rifles found in a sealed building in the Transilvanian factory town of Cugir. These were apparently to be issued for a planned massive troop build-up on the Hungarian border when Warsaw pact 
*tensions flared between the two member States. Luckily, cooler heads prevailed and a crisis was averted. The rifles were subsequently put in secure storage ‚Äì and forgotten, until now. The rifles feature a side folding stock, integral carry handle and bipod. As you can imagine, quantities are limited as only few hundred were ever produced ‚Äì and we bought them all! Each rifle comes with two 40 rd. mags. Barrel: 23" with a 1:10 twist, Overall: 34.25" (stock folded), 42" (stock extended), Weight: 11.8 lbs. Condition: Excellent."


I am Only selling because I am slimming down my collection. I actually have two of these rifles. My loss is your gain! Rifle is located in Newton, KS. I am willing to ship to an FFL. In-person transfers require you to be legal to purchase the rifle, willing to show ID, and sign a bill of sale or show a valid CCW.

postcontent:
For trade or sale, 2 Remington BDL rifles. Super condition and ready to use. 

1) .243 Win 22" barrel, walnut stock with skip line checkering and 4 screw hole butt plate. Bluing is near perfect.  Walker trigger, no recall issues.  Wood is very good with few dings, but nothing serious.  The gun is all original with a cheap but decent Tasco 3-9x40 scope.  Mount and rings are Leupold.  This rifle is a shooter.  It's sighted in at 200 yards.  Very light recoil but plenty of power.  No barrel warning, i.e. pre 1984. 

2) .300 Win Mag 24" barrel, walnut stock with skip line checkering.  Stock butt pad. Leupold mount and rings.  Scope is a variable Barska 10-40x50.  It's cheap but is quite clear up to about 25x and holds zero fine.  Bluing is super clear with honest wear at the muzzle only.  Walker trigger, no recall issues.  Has a nice sling and swivels.  Wood shows a few rubs from being carried.  No scratches or significant damage.  Sighted in at 200 yards. Very accurate and hard hitting cartridge.  I've successfully hunted with this gun out West.  Very few rounds through it.  Post 1984, but pre-hex head trigger guard screws.  
09/07/14 SOLD PENDING FUNDS--THANK YOU

Neither gun has a recalled trigger.  These are the "old" three screw rem triggers.  The .243 is about 3 pounds and breaks crispy.  The .300 is heavier, but can easily be adjusted down.  It's light but not as light as it could be.  
09/08/14 SOLD PENDING FUNDS--THANK YOU

Both were made long before Cerberus bought Remington and the build quality on these is by my standards, higher than the newest guns. There is nothing mechanically or really cosmetically wrong with either rifle.  To that end, the scopes are not "broken, throw aways" . They're not top shelf, but they hold zero and adjust.  These are hunting rifles and have been carried, but are both very accurate if you do your part.  I've shot very tight groups off of roll bails, recently out past 250 yards. If you like BDL's these are nice...   

Both guns are available for cash, face to face deals with Ohio residents. You'll need to show me your id and sign a receipt.  Shipping is available but must be to an FFL.  Payment would be by USPS money order only.  I'm placing a trade value of $1100.00 total for both guns as shown.  Sale value for both is the same.  Individually, the .300 could be bought for $650.00 and the .243 for $550.00.  So yes there is a $100.00 savings for a package buy.
